<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n25077h"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n25" href="#n25077h">N25 (VI.B.15)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n25all.htm#n25077h"> 77(h)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Finnic Otso bear / honeyeater / furrobed / the dance / apple of forest</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources"><font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> it is among the Finns that we find the most epuhemistic names applied to him. The forty-sixth rune of the Kalevala has for its theme the capture and killing of the &lsquo;sacred Otso&rsquo;, who is also addressed as <mark>the &lsquo;honey-eater,&rsquo; the &lsquo;fur-robed,&apos; the &lsquo;forest apple,&rsquo;</mark> who gives his life &lsquo;a sacrifice to Northland.&rsquo; When he is slain, W&auml;in&auml;m&ouml;inen, the old magician-hero of the story, sings the birth and fate of <mark>Otso</mark>, and artfully strives to make <mark>the dead grizzly</mark> believe that no cruel hand killed him, but that he fell <p class="set">&lsquo;From the fir-tree where he slumbered, <br>Tore his breast upon the branches, <br>Freely gave his life to others.&rsquo;</p> <small> Edward Clodd, <a name="ECTTT" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#ECTTT"><cite title="source">Tom Tit Tot</cite></a> (1898) 126-7</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Raphael transcription: <a name="c14046d" href="c14all.htm#c14046d">VI.C.14:046(d)</a>, <a name="c14046e" href="c14all.htm#c14046e">VI.C.14:046(e)</a>, <a name="c14046g" href="c14all.htm#c14046g">VI.C.14:046(g)</a>, <a name="c14046h" href="c14all.htm#c14046h">VI.C.14:046(h)</a>, <a name="c14046i" href="c14all.htm#c14046i">VI.C.14:046(i)</a> </mm></dd> </dd></dl>
